CommonFields.Title: Poly (butylene terephthalate)/silica nanocomposites prepared from cyclic butylene terephthalate
Author: Jiang, Zhenyu
Siengchin, Suchart
Zhou, Li-Min
Steeg, Markus
Karger-Kocsis, József
Man, Hau Chung
CommonFields.Location: Institute for Composite Materials (Institut für Verbundwerkstoffe GmbH), University of Kaiserslautern, 67663 Kaiserslautern, Germany

Drying-Evaporation.Description: All materials were dried at 80°C under vacuum for 12 h before processing to remove residual moisture.
All materials were dried at 80°C under vacuum for 12 h before processing to remove residual moisture.

Mixing.Description: The CBT resin mixed with nanoparticles was heated up to 200°C in a steel container until the resins were completely melted. The mixture was stirred by a wheel paddle (diameter: 7 cm) at a high speed of 1000 rpm for 15 min.

ChooseParameter.Other: The polymerization of CBT was conducted in situ in the presence of the catalyst at 200°C, and the whole system was kept at this temperature for 60 min to complete the ring opening reaction as well as crystallization.

MoldingInfo.Description: The obtained nanocomposites were crashed into small pieces, and then formed to sheets by compression molding whereby the bubbles in PBT could be removed effectively. During the compression molding, the PBT underwent a press force of 200 N at 250°C for 30 min.

Cooling.Description: After compression molding, the PBT samples were allowed to cool down naturally.

Transmission_Electron_Microscopy.Description: Transmission electronic microscopy (TEM) imaging was performed on a JEOL JEM-2010, operated at 200 kV accelerating voltage. To prepare specimens for TEM, ultra-thin sections (about 80 nm) of nanocomposites were cut using a RMC MT-XL ultramicrotome with diamond knife.

Scanning_Electron_Microscopy.Description: Scanning electronic microscopy (SEM) photos of the fracture surfaces of PBT/silica nanocompoistes were taken on a JEOL JSM-6490.

Dynamic_Mechanical_Analysis.Description: Dynamic mechanical analysis (DMA) was conducted also in three-point-bending mode at 1 Hz frequency using a TA Instruments Q800. The storage and loss moduli along with mechanical loss factor were determined as a function of temperature ranging from -100°C to +130°C. The amplitude applied was 15 lm, and the heating rate was fixed for 3°C/min.

Differential_Scanning_Calorimetry.Description: A differential scanning calorimeter (Mettler Toledo DSC 821) was used to measure the crystallinity of PBT nanocomposites.

Rheometery.Description: A controlled strain rheometer (Ares of Rheometric Scientific) was utilized to investigate the evolution of viscosity of CBT resin during the polymerization. The measurement was run in parallel plate configuration (plate diameter: 25 mm, gap between the plates: 1 mm) at 200°C with air convection temperature control.
